1
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:08,400
Man: This is the most famous
true African adventure;

2
00:01:08,400 --> 00:01:11,800
famous because
what took place at Tsavo

3
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:14,300
never happened before.

4
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:17,800
Colonel John Patterson
was there when it began...

5
00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:20,600
a fine lrish gentleman,

6
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:22,900
a brilliant engineer.

7
00:01:22,900 --> 00:01:24,400
He was my friend.

8
00:01:24,400 --> 00:01:27,200
My name is Samuel.

9
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:29,400
l was there.

10
00:01:30,700 --> 00:01:32,600
Remember this.

11
00:01:32,600 --> 00:01:38,100
Even the most impossible parts
of this story really happened.

12
00:01:45,800 --> 00:01:49,000
John Henry Patterson.
l'm Robert Beaumont.

13
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:51,900
Firm handshake.
l like that.

14
00:01:51,900 --> 00:01:54,300
Tells me a lot about you.
Do sit down.

15
00:01:57,600 --> 00:02:00,300
Now, why don't you
tell me about me?

16
00:02:00,300 --> 00:02:02,700
Well,
to get you started,

17
00:02:02,700 --> 00:02:05,600
many people find me handsome
with a wonderful smile.

18
00:02:05,600 --> 00:02:07,000
l'm sure you agree.

19
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,300
Winning personality,
heaps of charm.

20
00:02:10,300 --> 00:02:13,300
My wife is the game player
in the family, sir.

21
00:02:13,300 --> 00:02:15,000
[Chuckles]

22
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:16,900
Thank you, gentlemen.

23
00:02:18,600 --> 00:02:22,800
Look at me closely,
Colonel Patterson.

24
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:24,800
l'm a monster.

25
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:26,700
My only pleasure

26
00:02:26,700 --> 00:02:29,600
is tormenting those people
who work for me,

27
00:02:29,600 --> 00:02:31,300
people like yourself.

28
00:02:31,300 --> 00:02:34,000
Make one mistake,
and l promise you,

29
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,000
l'll make you hate me.

30
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:38,300
We're in a race,
Colonel,

31
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:40,900
and the prize
is nothing less

32
00:02:40,900 --> 00:02:43,000
than the continent
of Africa.

33
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,400
We are building the most expensive
and daring railroad in history

34
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:49,600
for the glorious purpose
of saving Africa from the Africans

35
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:51,500
and, of course,
to end slavery.

36
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:54,200
Our competitors are the Germans
and the French.

37
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:57,000
We are ahead,
and we will stay ahead,

38
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:00,000
provided you do what
l've hired you to do:

39
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:03,100
Build a bridge
across the river Tsavo

40
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:06,300
and be finished
in 5 months.

41
00:03:06,300 --> 00:03:07,800
Can you do that?

42
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:09,800
l am sure you've
examined my record.

43
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:12,100
You know l've never
been late on a bridge.

44
00:03:12,100 --> 00:03:14,800
l'm well aware of your
distinguished record, Colonel,

45
00:03:14,800 --> 00:03:17,000
but let me
humbly remind you,

46
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:19,000
you've never built
in Africa.

47
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:20,300
l have in lndia.

48
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:23,100
Each country presents
its own challenges.

49
00:03:23,100 --> 00:03:26,900
You'll need all your confidence,
l promise you.

50
00:03:26,900 --> 00:03:28,200
l love Africa.

51
00:03:28,200 --> 00:03:30,200
l've always wanted
to go there,

52
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:32,300
and if l may
speak personally,

53
00:03:32,300 --> 00:03:35,300
my wife is having
our firstborn in 6 months,

54
00:03:35,300 --> 00:03:38,600
and l promised her
l'd be there for the birth,

55
00:03:38,600 --> 00:03:40,800
and l always
keep my word.

56
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:42,500
Very moving,
Colonel Patterson.

57
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:45,400
l'm touched
you confided in me,

58
00:03:45,400 --> 00:03:49,100
but l really don't give a shit
about your upcoming litter.

59
00:03:49,100 --> 00:03:53,000
l've made you
with this assignment.

60
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:54,800
Don't make me break you.

61
00:03:56,400 --> 00:03:59,000
You won't have
the opportunity.

62
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,400
Any other words
of encouragement?

63
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:06,600
Then l have
a train to catch.

64
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:11,800
[Sounds From Crowded Street]

65
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:21,400
Woman: Tell me
about Beaumont.

66
00:04:21,400 --> 00:04:23,400
Does he understand
how brilliant you are,

67
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:25,600
how lucky he is
to have you?

68
00:04:25,600 --> 00:04:28,800
lt was embarrassing.
The man showered me with praise.

69
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:30,400
Oh, dear.

70
00:04:33,200 --> 00:04:35,600
You're getting that
downtrodden look again.

71
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:37,700
No. No.

72
00:04:39,400 --> 00:04:41,800
l would never have taken this
had we known sooner.

73
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:44,000
And you would
have been in agony,

74
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:46,200
and it would have
been my fault.

75
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:49,000
You've been desperate to see Africa
all your life.

76
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:50,500
There may be
difficulties.

77
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:52,900
There will be.
There always are.

78
00:04:52,900 --> 00:04:55,800
Which only means
that our son and l--

79
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:57,700
note my confidence--

80
00:04:57,700 --> 00:05:01,000
will have an excuse
to come and visit you.

81
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:03,000
[Whistle Blows]

82
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,200
Man: All aboard!

83
00:05:05,200 --> 00:05:06,600
Come along.

84
00:05:06,600 --> 00:05:08,500
Put me
on the train.

85
00:05:09,700 --> 00:05:11,400
You go.

86
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:20,200
Such a gentleman.

87
00:05:26,500 --> 00:05:29,600
l am desperate to see Africa,
but it's just a place.

88
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:31,800
You build bridges,
John.

89
00:05:31,800 --> 00:05:34,800
You have to go where
the rivers are.

90
00:05:40,200 --> 00:05:41,600
Bye.

91
00:05:56,200 --> 00:05:58,200
[Men Speaking
Foreign Language]

92
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:15,300
Colonel Patterson.

93
00:06:15,300 --> 00:06:17,000
Patterson:
No, thank you.

94
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:18,200
Colonel Patterson, yes?

95
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:20,900
No, thank you.
No, thank you. No, thank you.

96
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:23,400
Welcome to Africa, sir,
and good morning.

97
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:26,500
Angus Starling.
l am to assist you at Tsavo.

98
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:28,500
But Beaumont will have
told you that, surely.

99
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:31,800
No, actually. He did give me
his monster speech.

100
00:06:31,800 --> 00:06:34,600
That. Oh, l know
Robert seems dreadful,

101
00:06:34,600 --> 00:06:38,100
but once you truly get to know
the man, he's much worse.

102
00:06:38,100 --> 00:06:40,400
Ha ha! And l'm one
of his defenders.

103
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:42,900
Forget him for now.
Follow me, sir.

104
00:06:42,900 --> 00:06:45,000
lt's your first trip
to Africa, yes?

105
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,000
Good, because l've reserved
the best seats on the train.

106
00:07:16,500 --> 00:07:18,400
Starling: They're amazing,
aren't they?

107
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:21,000
You know the most
amazing thing about them?

108
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:23,700
They sleep only
5 minutes a day.

109
00:07:30,500 --> 00:07:31,800
Don't like them much.

110
00:07:31,800 --> 00:07:33,200
The females
are bigger.

111
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:35,000
Only animals here
like that.

112
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:37,300
Have to be,
or they wouldn't survive

113
00:07:37,300 --> 00:07:39,400
because the males
eat the young.

114
00:07:52,200 --> 00:07:54,200
Anything special
about them?

115
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:57,200
Well, it's just that they fart
through their mouths.

116
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:59,500
l bet they don't
kiss very much.

117
00:07:59,500 --> 00:08:02,400
l've lived in Africa for a year,
and l don't know what you know.

118
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:04,300
How long have you
been here?

119
00:08:04,300 --> 00:08:06,200
Just about 24 hours.

120
00:08:06,200 --> 00:08:09,600
But l've been longing
for this all my life.

121
00:08:50,800 --> 00:08:52,700
[Steam Whistle Blows]

122
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:03,300
Welcome to Tsavo.

123
00:09:05,100 --> 00:09:07,000
[Whistle Blows]

124
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:08,500
[Bell Clanging]

125
00:09:13,900 --> 00:09:15,900
[Man Speaking
Foreign Language]

126
00:09:19,600 --> 00:09:21,100
Starling: Samuel!

127
00:09:21,100 --> 00:09:24,200
Samuel's camp liaison,
absolutely indispensable.

128
00:09:24,200 --> 00:09:26,300
He's the only man here
everyone trusts.

129
00:09:26,300 --> 00:09:27,700
Does he
speak English?

130
00:09:27,700 --> 00:09:29,800
And very poor French.

131
00:09:29,800 --> 00:09:32,400
Samuel,
Colonel John Patterson.

132
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:33,800
The bridge builder.

133
00:09:33,800 --> 00:09:35,800
We've been getting
ready for you.

134
00:09:35,800 --> 00:09:37,900
Good. l'd like to
see the bridge site.

135
00:09:37,900 --> 00:09:40,400
l've got some
medical supplies to deliver.

136
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:42,200
Come along to the hospital
when you're done.

137
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:44,500
l'll bring him,
Angus.

138
00:09:48,700 --> 00:09:50,600
Where are you from,
Samuel?

139
00:09:50,600 --> 00:09:52,700
That way,
beyond those mountains.

140
00:09:52,700 --> 00:09:54,600
l'm from...

141
00:09:54,600 --> 00:09:56,200
over there.

142
00:10:31,300 --> 00:10:34,400
[Man Speaking
Foreign Language]

143
00:10:42,200 --> 00:10:45,000
Patterson: Everything
seems to be under control.

144
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:47,900
Thank you. lf it is,
it's a miracle.

145
00:10:47,900 --> 00:10:49,400
Why is that?

146
00:10:49,400 --> 00:10:50,900
The truth is,

147
00:10:50,900 --> 00:10:53,400
the workers don't
like each other at all.

148
00:10:53,400 --> 00:10:55,600
Obviously, the Africans
hate the lndians,

149
00:10:55,600 --> 00:10:58,200
but the lndians
also hate other lndians.

150
00:10:58,200 --> 00:11:01,200
The Hindus believe
cows are sacred,

151
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:04,000
while the Muslims
eat the cows.

152
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:05,900
[Cows Lowing]

153
00:11:05,900 --> 00:11:07,500
[Samuel Speaking
Foreign Language]

154
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:09,400
Do you eat a cow?

155
00:11:09,400 --> 00:11:10,800
Of course.

156
00:11:10,800 --> 00:11:13,400
l've worked with
both Hindu and Muslim.

157
00:11:13,400 --> 00:11:14,600
Perhaps l can help.

158
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:17,200
You can certainly try.
lt won't work.

159
00:11:17,200 --> 00:11:19,100
Nothing works here.

160
00:11:19,100 --> 00:11:22,700
Tsavo is the worst
place in the world.

161
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:37,200
Advance camp
is across there.

162
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:38,700
How many workers?

163
00:11:38,700 --> 00:11:40,400
3,000 men
laying track.

164
00:11:40,400 --> 00:11:43,000
Even though your bridge
is not yet built,

165
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:46,200
each day they move 2 miles
further away.

166
00:11:57,800 --> 00:12:00,200
Samuel: Did it look like this
in your mind?

167
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:01,700
No.

168
00:12:03,100 --> 00:12:04,600
This is more difficult.

169
00:12:04,600 --> 00:12:06,300
Should be difficult.

170
00:12:06,300 --> 00:12:11,300
What better job in all the world
than build a bridge?

171
00:12:11,300 --> 00:12:13,200
Bring land over water.

172
00:12:14,800 --> 00:12:17,400
Bring worlds together.

173
00:12:17,400 --> 00:12:19,000
Starling:
Finish your tour?

174
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,800
Patterson: ls this
mostly malaria?

175
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:23,400
Yes, but their suffering
is only transitory...

176
00:12:23,400 --> 00:12:25,900
once they accept God
into their hearts.

177
00:12:25,900 --> 00:12:28,700
Man: That's just
vomitus talk, Mr. Starling.

178
00:12:28,700 --> 00:12:30,800
Poor bastards
will get even sicker

179
00:12:30,800 --> 00:12:32,500
if you don't
shut up.

180
00:12:34,100 --> 00:12:36,000
David Hawthorne.

181
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:37,900
l'm, um...

182
00:12:37,900 --> 00:12:39,800
This is my hospital.

183
00:12:39,800 --> 00:12:42,700
And my advice
to you is...

184
00:12:42,700 --> 00:12:44,900
don't get sick.

185
00:12:44,900 --> 00:12:47,600
Ha ha! That was meant
to be charming.

186
00:12:47,600 --> 00:12:50,100
Sorry. l seem to
have lost the knack.

187
00:12:50,100 --> 00:12:51,600
You never had it.

188
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:54,600
Angus and l don't
like each other much.

189
00:12:54,600 --> 00:12:58,200
l am also a liaison
between these two.

190
00:12:58,200 --> 00:13:00,600
Clearly, you don't share
Beaumont's vision.

191
00:13:00,600 --> 00:13:03,500
This?
This is a sham.

192
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:05,400
Who needs it?
lt's ridiculous.

193
00:13:05,400 --> 00:13:08,500
lt's only being built
to protect the ivory trade,

194
00:13:08,500 --> 00:13:10,200
make rich men
richer.

195
00:13:10,200 --> 00:13:12,500
Then why stay,
Doctor?

196
00:13:12,500 --> 00:13:14,800
Who else
would hire me?

197
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:17,700
Beat you to it,
didn't l?

198
00:13:17,700 --> 00:13:19,000
Dr. Hawthorne--

199
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:21,000
Oh, yes.
l almost forgot.

200
00:13:22,500 --> 00:13:25,900
You seem to have brought
bad luck with you. Come here.

201
00:13:25,900 --> 00:13:27,900
This is Karim,
one of my orderlies.

202
00:13:27,900 --> 00:13:30,200
He was attacked by
a man-eater earlier today.

203
00:13:30,200 --> 00:13:31,800
A man-eater attacks,

204
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:33,200
and you're
such a buffoon,

205
00:13:33,200 --> 00:13:35,200
you almost forget
to mention it.

206
00:13:35,200 --> 00:13:37,100
His injuries
are only slight.

207
00:13:37,100 --> 00:13:39,800
Been riding his donkey
not far from here,

208
00:13:39,800 --> 00:13:42,200
when suddenly
a lion sprang on them.

209
00:13:42,200 --> 00:13:45,600
Donkey took the brunt of it,
then the lion ran off.

210
00:13:45,600 --> 00:13:47,100
Thank you, Karim.

211
00:13:48,800 --> 00:13:51,700
Now, l know this is
your first day,

212
00:13:51,700 --> 00:13:54,400
and you must be
tired...

213
00:13:54,400 --> 00:13:56,200
but, um...

214
00:13:56,200 --> 00:13:58,600
what are you going
to do about it?

215
00:13:58,600 --> 00:14:01,300
With any luck,
l'll sort it out this evening.

216
00:14:02,900 --> 00:14:05,800
l don't suppose
l could come and watch.

217
00:14:05,800 --> 00:14:07,700
Have you ever
hunted?

218
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:09,400
Well, not exactly.

219
00:14:09,400 --> 00:14:11,700
l've never been
very adventurous.

220
00:14:14,800 --> 00:14:16,700
Can you keep quiet?

221
00:14:21,100 --> 00:14:23,700
l hate to be a bother,
John, but--

222
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:25,200
Shh!

223
00:14:28,600 --> 00:14:31,900
The cramp
is getting worse.

224
00:14:33,400 --> 00:14:36,800
The pain is actually
quite unbearable now.

225
00:14:36,800 --> 00:14:39,800
You'll just have to
cope with it, Angus.

226
00:14:39,800 --> 00:14:42,300
That is precisely
my plan...

227
00:14:42,300 --> 00:14:44,300
but back at my tent.

228
00:14:45,700 --> 00:14:48,500
You'll be dead before
you ever get to your tent.

229
00:14:48,500 --> 00:14:50,200
The lion will eat you.

230
00:14:50,200 --> 00:14:51,700
l know.

231
00:14:58,200 --> 00:15:01,000
ls this the best way
to hunt a lion?

232
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:04,600
l don't know.
l've never even seen one.

233
00:15:06,700 --> 00:15:08,800
[Owl Screeches
And Flies Away]

234
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:36,500
[Donkey Brays]

235
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:42,300
[Lion Growls]

236
00:15:43,300 --> 00:15:44,800
No!

237
00:15:50,800 --> 00:15:53,000
Aah!

238
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:55,000
Starling: One shot!

239
00:15:57,100 --> 00:15:58,500
Samuel: One shot!

240
00:15:58,500 --> 00:16:01,800
Patterson has made
the night safe again!

241
00:16:01,800 --> 00:16:04,300
[Speaking
Foreign Language]

242
00:16:06,300 --> 00:16:09,200
[Men Cheering]

243
00:16:15,800 --> 00:16:18,500
My God,
you sorted it out.

244
00:16:22,100 --> 00:16:25,600
Samuel: There is nothing like
the fear a man-eater brings.

245
00:16:25,600 --> 00:16:28,800
They own the night
and kill so quickly.

246
00:16:28,800 --> 00:16:31,000
lt was clear to the men

247
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:34,300
that Patterson was willing
to take risks for them.

248
00:16:34,300 --> 00:16:38,100
That one shot
had taken their fears away.

249
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:43,100
Patterson:
All right, Angus.

250
00:16:43,100 --> 00:16:47,200
l've decided to have you and Mahina
oversee the foundation piers.

251
00:16:49,800 --> 00:16:54,200
Of course, the hardest part
about building a bridge

252
00:16:54,200 --> 00:16:56,500
is the foundation piers,

253
00:16:56,500 --> 00:16:59,400
and for that task,
l'm giving you...

254
00:16:59,400 --> 00:17:01,200
4 thrilling weeks.

255
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:03,600
Aren't we full
of ourselves today.

256
00:17:03,600 --> 00:17:06,600
l think it's
because of the lion.

257
00:17:06,600 --> 00:17:07,900
Uh, John--

258
00:17:07,900 --> 00:17:10,700
You know, l also
have killed a lion.

259
00:17:10,700 --> 00:17:13,300
How many shots
did you need?

260
00:17:13,300 --> 00:17:14,800
l used my hands.

261
00:17:14,800 --> 00:17:16,600
Oh.

262
00:17:16,600 --> 00:17:19,700
Uh, John, 4 weeks
is just not enough time.

263
00:17:19,700 --> 00:17:22,300
You'll just have to
use your hands.

264
00:17:24,100 --> 00:17:25,800
[Mahina Laughs]

265
00:19:04,200 --> 00:19:06,000
[Samuel Speaking
Foreign Language]

266
00:19:10,500 --> 00:19:12,400
Hey, Samuel!

267
00:19:18,200 --> 00:19:21,900
[Men Cheering]

268
00:19:51,200 --> 00:19:53,100
Come in.

269
00:19:56,300 --> 00:19:58,200
One shot.

270
00:20:02,200 --> 00:20:05,200
The claws of
the lion you killed.

271
00:20:06,900 --> 00:20:08,300
Thank you.

272
00:20:08,300 --> 00:20:11,400
lt will always
remind me of Africa.

273
00:20:11,400 --> 00:20:14,300
lt is meant
to remind you of courage.

274
00:20:14,300 --> 00:20:17,300
lt will also
protect you.

275
00:20:17,300 --> 00:20:18,900
Wear it.

276
00:20:28,700 --> 00:20:30,100
Patterson's voice:
Darling...

277
00:20:30,100 --> 00:20:32,000
you know how God invented liquor

278
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:34,400
so the lrish
wouldn't rule the world?

279
00:20:34,400 --> 00:20:36,500
Well, l sometimes think
he invented being bullheaded

280
00:20:36,500 --> 00:20:38,700
so we could be
the best at something,

281
00:20:38,700 --> 00:20:40,500
for when this bridge
is finished,

282
00:20:40,500 --> 00:20:43,400
it will have nothing to do
with my engineering skill

283
00:20:43,400 --> 00:20:45,500
and all to do
with my stubbornness.

284
00:20:45,500 --> 00:20:47,000
Africa...

285
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:49,000
lt changes everything
l plan,

286
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:52,300
yet still we are somehow
ahead of schedule.

287
00:20:52,300 --> 00:20:55,200
Mahina, my foreman,
deserves so much credit.

288
00:20:55,200 --> 00:20:57,100
The man is a marvel.

289
00:20:57,100 --> 00:20:58,500
Oh, another marvel.

290
00:20:58,500 --> 00:21:02,500
Starling has actually convinced
some of the natives to convert.

291
00:21:02,500 --> 00:21:06,200
l cannot wait to show
this beautiful country to you.

292
00:21:06,200 --> 00:21:08,000
Love, John.

293
00:21:37,900 --> 00:21:39,500
[Lion Growls]

294
00:21:39,500 --> 00:21:41,600
Aah!

295
00:21:41,600 --> 00:21:43,300
Man: Simba! Simba!

296
00:21:43,300 --> 00:21:45,600
[Men Shouting]

297
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:49,100
[Lion Growling]

298
00:22:14,300 --> 00:22:16,500
Aah!

299
00:22:26,500 --> 00:22:28,600
[Screeching]

300
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:46,400
Hawthorne: What the lion
must have done was...

301
00:22:46,400 --> 00:22:49,500
lick his skin off
so he could drink his blood.

302
00:22:49,500 --> 00:22:52,900
Then he feasted on him,
starting with his feet.

303
00:22:54,700 --> 00:22:56,500
Lions don't
eat this way.

304
00:22:56,500 --> 00:22:59,100
Are you sure
this was a lion?

305
00:22:59,100 --> 00:23:00,800
We followed his tracks.

306
00:23:02,900 --> 00:23:06,900
What sort of lion could
carry off someone Mahina's size?

307
00:23:06,900 --> 00:23:11,100
[Man Speaking
Foreign Language]

308
00:23:23,200 --> 00:23:26,300
Samuel: Terror had now
built a home inside us

309
00:23:26,300 --> 00:23:28,400
and would not leave,

310
00:23:28,400 --> 00:23:30,900
because if Mahina,
who was so powerful,

311
00:23:30,900 --> 00:23:32,600
could not save himself,

312
00:23:32,600 --> 00:23:35,400
what could
the rest of us do?

313
00:23:48,500 --> 00:23:50,500
[Cocks Rifle]

314
00:23:55,700 --> 00:23:58,000
# Too-ra-li #

315
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:01,200
# Too-ra-lee #

316
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:04,200
# Oh, it's 6 miles
from Bangor... #

317
00:24:07,400 --> 00:24:09,400
# Too-ra-li #

318
00:24:09,400 --> 00:24:12,000
# Too-ra-lee #

319
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:15,800
# Oh, it's 6 miles
from Bangor... #

320
00:24:35,500 --> 00:24:38,500
[Lion Roaring]

321
00:24:38,500 --> 00:24:40,600
[Man Shouting]

322
00:25:03,600 --> 00:25:05,700
[Men Speaking
Foreign Language]

323
00:25:10,100 --> 00:25:13,300
Man: You want us to work
even if we have to die to do it.

324
00:25:13,300 --> 00:25:15,200
[Samuel Speaking
Foreign Language]

325
00:25:15,200 --> 00:25:18,100
Patterson: Why is there
no work being done?

326
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:21,100
Malaria epidemic.
Very sudden.

327
00:25:21,100 --> 00:25:24,000
There is no reason
for fear.

328
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:26,800
On that l choose
to remain dubious.

329
00:25:26,800 --> 00:25:28,900
2 are dead now
in 2 nights.

330
00:25:28,900 --> 00:25:30,400
A second?

331
00:25:30,400 --> 00:25:34,200
Far end of the camp,
a man wandering alone at night.

332
00:25:34,200 --> 00:25:37,400
There's even less of him
than there was of Mahina.

333
00:25:37,400 --> 00:25:40,800
lt's too soon for a lion
to kill from hunger.

334
00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:42,700
Samuel: ln our village,

335
00:25:42,700 --> 00:25:45,400
we construct thornbush fences
around where we live.

336
00:25:45,400 --> 00:25:48,400
Big burning fires at night,
that keeps the lion away.

337
00:25:48,400 --> 00:25:51,200
Good. Get started.

338
00:25:51,200 --> 00:25:53,100
And a strict curfew:

339
00:25:53,100 --> 00:25:56,000
No one is allowed out
of their tent at night.

340
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:00,400
Abdullah, you'll send half your men
with Samuel to help build these fences.

341
00:26:00,400 --> 00:26:02,100
The other half
you'll take to the bridge.

342
00:26:02,100 --> 00:26:05,900
l'll sort this out. l will kill
the lion, and l will build the bridge.

343
00:26:05,900 --> 00:26:07,400
Of course you will.

344
00:26:09,100 --> 00:26:12,000
You are white.
You can do anything.

345
00:26:13,700 --> 00:26:18,500
lt would be a mistake not to work
together on this thing, Abdullah.

346
00:26:23,800 --> 00:26:25,900
[Samuel Speaking
Foreign Language]

347
00:26:45,400 --> 00:26:48,400
[Singing
ln Foreign Language]

348
00:26:48,400 --> 00:26:50,500
No! lt's got
to be tighter!

349
00:26:50,500 --> 00:26:54,100
You see? This has
got to be a wall!

350
00:27:06,700 --> 00:27:08,300
What a good week.

351
00:27:08,300 --> 00:27:10,400
You mean nobody died?

352
00:27:10,400 --> 00:27:12,100
Well, we all
worked together.

353
00:27:12,100 --> 00:27:15,000
Worthy deeds
were accomplished.

354
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,500
l like the labor.

355
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:22,400
My mother insisted
on piano lessons.

356
00:27:22,400 --> 00:27:27,000
Broke the dear woman's heart when
it turned out l was tone-deaf,

357
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:31,000
but she was always on at me
to be careful with my hands.

358
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:33,000
l like the blood.

359
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:34,900
ls that so strange?

360
00:27:34,900 --> 00:27:36,200
No.

361
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:38,400
Oh, yes.

362
00:27:38,400 --> 00:27:40,400
l think so.

363
00:27:40,400 --> 00:27:41,900
Here it comes, Samuel.

364
00:27:41,900 --> 00:27:47,200
Even you two must admit it is glorious
what man can accomplish.

365
00:27:47,200 --> 00:27:50,400
With one common splendid goal,
there are no limits.

366
00:27:50,400 --> 00:27:54,100
Think what will be done when we all
have God's warmth in our hearts.

367
00:27:54,100 --> 00:27:56,100
[Snoring]

368
00:27:57,600 --> 00:28:00,900
l am immune
to your disdain.

369
00:28:00,900 --> 00:28:02,100
[Laughing]

370
00:28:02,100 --> 00:28:05,200
When l came here,
l had one small goal:

371
00:28:05,200 --> 00:28:07,800
to convert the entire continent
of Africa.

372
00:28:07,800 --> 00:28:11,200
Now l've decided to move on
to something really difficult.

373
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:15,900
l will not rest until both of you
are safely in the fold.

374
00:28:15,900 --> 00:28:17,400
Patterson: l'm
beyond conversion.

375
00:28:17,400 --> 00:28:18,900
My mother's
Roman Catholic,

376
00:28:18,900 --> 00:28:20,400
and my father's
a protestant.

377
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:21,500
[Samuel Chuckles]

378
00:28:21,500 --> 00:28:24,200
l have 4 wives.

379
00:28:24,200 --> 00:28:25,700
Good luck.

380
00:28:28,200 --> 00:28:30,100
The struggle
is the glory.

381
00:28:30,100 --> 00:28:32,000
[Laughing]

382
00:28:45,400 --> 00:28:48,900
[Men Speaking
Foreign Language]

383
00:29:01,400 --> 00:29:03,600
Samuel: For you.

384
00:29:03,600 --> 00:29:05,500
Thank you, Samuel.

385
00:29:07,400 --> 00:29:08,400
Good news.

386
00:29:08,400 --> 00:29:11,200
l expect so...
from my wife.

387
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:17,100
You like her?

388
00:29:18,400 --> 00:29:19,600
Very much.

389
00:29:22,100 --> 00:29:24,700
l don't like
any of mine.

390
00:29:32,700 --> 00:29:35,200
[Speaking
Foreign Language]

391
00:29:43,500 --> 00:29:46,700
Mrs. Patterson's voice: Darling,
the big excitement yesterday

392
00:29:46,700 --> 00:29:50,000
was when some schoolchildren
spotted a whale.

393
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:51,900
They were
looking at me, John.

394
00:29:51,900 --> 00:29:57,000
That was an attempt at humor,
but l don't feel very funny these days.

395
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:58,600
Anyway, after our son--

396
00:29:58,600 --> 00:30:01,200
You'll note l still have
total confidence--

397
00:30:01,200 --> 00:30:06,400
Well, after he's born, l think travel
might be the order of the day.

398
00:30:06,400 --> 00:30:09,400
As he kicks me at night,
l'm quite sure he's telling me

399
00:30:09,400 --> 00:30:13,800
he definitely
wants to come to Africa.

400
00:30:13,800 --> 00:30:15,700
Thought you might
need reminding.

401
00:30:15,700 --> 00:30:17,400
[Lion Roars]

402
00:30:17,400 --> 00:30:20,600
[Men Shouting]

403
00:30:28,300 --> 00:30:29,600
Aah!

404
00:30:52,700 --> 00:30:54,700
Move! Move yourselves! Move!

405
00:31:08,400 --> 00:31:11,700
Patterson: Angus!
Stay here.

406
00:31:24,800 --> 00:31:25,800
[Thud]

407
00:31:27,300 --> 00:31:29,800
[Lion Growls]

408
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:33,400
[Lion Growls]

409
00:31:33,400 --> 00:31:34,600
[Crash]

410
00:31:52,400 --> 00:31:55,000
[Roaring]

411
00:32:14,300 --> 00:32:16,200
[Roars]

412
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:19,200
[Lion Roaring]

413
00:32:25,800 --> 00:32:26,900
Starling: Oh, God!

414
00:32:29,100 --> 00:32:30,200
[Bones Cracking]

415
00:32:31,900 --> 00:32:34,900
[Lions Growling]

416
00:32:39,100 --> 00:32:41,100
[Gunshot]

417
00:32:41,100 --> 00:32:42,600
Jesus.

418
00:32:42,600 --> 00:32:44,600
There are 2 of them.

419
00:32:45,700 --> 00:32:49,600
[Samuel Speaking
Foreign Language]

420
00:32:49,600 --> 00:32:51,700
Patterson: Oh, Jesus.

421
00:32:59,900 --> 00:33:02,300
And the king spake
and said unto Daniel,

422
00:33:02,300 --> 00:33:04,200
''Oh, Daniel, servant
of the living God,

423
00:33:04,200 --> 00:33:06,600
is thy god, whom thou
servest continually,

424
00:33:06,600 --> 00:33:09,000
able to deliver thee
from the lions?''

425
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:12,300
And Daniel said unto the king,
''Oh, King, live forever.

426
00:33:12,300 --> 00:33:14,700
My god hath sent his angels
and hath shut the lions' mouths

427
00:33:14,700 --> 00:33:16,200
that they
have not hurt me,

428
00:33:16,200 --> 00:33:20,000
forasmuch as before Him,
innocency was found in me.

429
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:23,700
And as before thee, oh, King,
have l done no hurt.

430
00:33:23,700 --> 00:33:25,700
Have l done no hurt.''

431
00:33:28,100 --> 00:33:31,600
Samuel: The men called them
the Ghost and the Darkness.

432
00:33:31,600 --> 00:33:33,600
There were 2 of them,

433
00:33:33,600 --> 00:33:36,100
and that had never
happened before

434
00:33:36,100 --> 00:33:39,200
because man-eaters
are always alone.

435
00:33:39,200 --> 00:33:42,200
They owned the nights,

436
00:33:42,200 --> 00:33:44,900
but they also
attacked in daylight,

437
00:33:44,900 --> 00:33:47,800
alone or together,
without fear or reason.

438
00:33:47,800 --> 00:33:50,800
Some thought
they were not lions at all

439
00:33:50,800 --> 00:33:54,000
but the spirits of dead medicine men
come back to spread madness.

440
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:56,000
For others,
they were the devil,

441
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:59,900
sent to stop the white men
from owning the world.

442
00:33:59,900 --> 00:34:04,400
l believed this:
That they were evil,

443
00:34:04,400 --> 00:34:07,400
and what better ground
for evil to walk than Tsavo?

444
00:34:07,400 --> 00:34:10,300
Because this is what
the word Tsavo means:

445
00:34:10,300 --> 00:34:12,300
A place of slaughter.

446
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:19,900
Patterson: l've
given you my word.

447
00:34:19,900 --> 00:34:22,100
Why haven't you told them
help is on the way?

448
00:34:22,100 --> 00:34:24,100
lt's too late now,
Mr. Patterson.

449
00:34:24,100 --> 00:34:27,000
lt's not too late. Abdullah, they will
listen to you. You must make them stay.

450
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:29,600
They are too afraid to work.
They want to go home.

451
00:34:29,600 --> 00:34:31,800
Be content that l
have decided to stay.

452
00:34:31,800 --> 00:34:35,500
[Train Whistle Blowing]

453
00:34:35,500 --> 00:34:37,700
Beaumont
is on that train.

454
00:34:37,700 --> 00:34:40,500
lf he sees this mess,
you will lose your job.

455
00:34:40,500 --> 00:34:43,400
So will you, sir.
That's all, really, you care about.

456
00:34:45,100 --> 00:34:47,300
Oh, for Christ...

457
00:34:53,800 --> 00:34:55,600
Well, then,
you go, too.

458
00:34:55,600 --> 00:34:57,200
You lack
the courage to lead.

459
00:34:57,200 --> 00:34:59,800
Go. Tell
all your men to go,

460
00:34:59,800 --> 00:35:01,600
but l will
kill the lions,

461
00:35:01,600 --> 00:35:03,900
and l will
build the bridge,

462
00:35:03,900 --> 00:35:06,400
and you,
you must go home

463
00:35:06,400 --> 00:35:10,200
and tell the wives of the men
who died working here...

464
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:15,200
that you fled with the others
because you could not master your fear.

465
00:35:36,700 --> 00:35:38,100
Welcome to Tsavo.

466
00:35:39,400 --> 00:35:40,500
Pleasant journey?

467
00:35:40,500 --> 00:35:42,700
How could it be?
l hate Africa.

468
00:35:45,700 --> 00:35:48,300
That's a lovely sound.
They seem happy.

469
00:35:49,600 --> 00:35:52,300
[Singing
ln Foreign Language]

470
00:35:54,600 --> 00:35:55,900
Don't they, though?

471
00:35:55,900 --> 00:35:57,500
So work's going well?

472
00:35:57,500 --> 00:35:59,200
What of my request
for soldiers?

473
00:35:59,200 --> 00:36:01,400
l told you before.
You're on your own.

474
00:36:01,400 --> 00:36:03,000
There will be
no soldiers here.

475
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:05,000
l promised my men
protection.

476
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:06,700
Where's Starling? A while back,
he ordered some bibles.

477
00:36:06,700 --> 00:36:08,300
l've brought them.

478
00:36:08,300 --> 00:36:09,500
ls he here?

479
00:36:11,700 --> 00:36:14,000
Where is he?
Where's Starling?

480
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:15,700
Here he comes.

481
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:26,100
What happened?

482
00:36:26,100 --> 00:36:28,400
l'll show you.

483
00:36:34,200 --> 00:36:37,800
Nothing wrong
with these people.

484
00:36:37,800 --> 00:36:38,700
They're afraid.

485
00:36:38,700 --> 00:36:40,300
What the hell
is going on?

486
00:36:41,500 --> 00:36:44,600
The Ghost and the Darkness
have come.

487
00:36:44,600 --> 00:36:45,800
ln English.

488
00:36:45,800 --> 00:36:49,100
lt's what the natives
are calling the lions.

489
00:36:49,100 --> 00:36:50,900
There's a legend here.

490
00:36:50,900 --> 00:36:54,100
2 man-eaters are
making all the trouble.

491
00:36:54,100 --> 00:36:57,000
Well, this is Africa, Patterson.
l thought you were a hunter.

492
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:00,700
lt's not that simple.
These lions are...

493
00:37:02,800 --> 00:37:04,400
not like lions.

494
00:37:05,700 --> 00:37:07,500
How many
have they killed?

495
00:37:08,900 --> 00:37:11,200
About 30,
l should think.

496
00:37:13,900 --> 00:37:16,000
Christ!

497
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:19,800
Beaumont: You've been here 3 months,
and already you're behind schedule.

498
00:37:19,800 --> 00:37:24,000
Don't you know that the French
and the Germans are right behind you?

499
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:29,000
And l don't care about you,
and l don't care about the 30 dead.

500
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:31,600
l care about
my knighthood.

501
00:37:32,700 --> 00:37:35,600
As to your request
for troops,

502
00:37:35,600 --> 00:37:39,000
do we wish the world to think that
the builders of the British empire

503
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:41,300
are afraid
to do their job

504
00:37:41,300 --> 00:37:45,200
because of a few minor difficulties
with the local wildlife?

505
00:37:45,200 --> 00:37:47,200
l don't think so.

506
00:37:47,200 --> 00:37:49,600
So what are you
planning to do?

507
00:37:53,500 --> 00:37:55,400
l'm calling it
my contraption.

508
00:37:55,400 --> 00:37:58,900
l placed it here because
this is the area of the camp

509
00:37:58,900 --> 00:38:01,100
where the lions
have attacked the most.

510
00:38:02,600 --> 00:38:04,400
l'm surrounding it
with a boma--

511
00:38:04,400 --> 00:38:05,300
What?

512
00:38:05,300 --> 00:38:06,600
A fence--

513
00:38:06,600 --> 00:38:10,000
except for this small area here
opposite this door.

514
00:38:11,400 --> 00:38:15,400
Just what kind of lunacy
are we dealing with here? Hmm?

515
00:38:22,200 --> 00:38:26,000
On the other side of these bars
will be bait, human bait.

516
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:27,900
l'll start things off.

517
00:38:27,900 --> 00:38:32,300
About here will be a tripwire
for this sliding door.

518
00:38:34,600 --> 00:38:36,500
Genius!

519
00:38:36,500 --> 00:38:39,000
The beast will enter,
tripping the wire,

520
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:41,800
the door will slide down
behind him, trapping him.

521
00:38:41,800 --> 00:38:44,200
You, meanwhile,
safe behind your bars,

522
00:38:44,200 --> 00:38:46,600
will have the beast
at your mercy

523
00:38:46,600 --> 00:38:49,800
and will shoot him
at your leisure.

524
00:38:51,200 --> 00:38:53,900
Are you running
a high fever, man?

525
00:38:53,900 --> 00:38:56,200
How could you conceive
of something so idiotic?

526
00:38:56,200 --> 00:38:58,600
l didn't conceive of it
for the lions.

527
00:38:58,600 --> 00:39:00,800
lt was for a tiger
in lndia.

528
00:39:00,800 --> 00:39:02,300
And it worked?

529
00:39:02,300 --> 00:39:05,100
ln point of fact,
it didn't,

530
00:39:05,100 --> 00:39:08,100
but l'm convinced
the theory is sound.

531
00:39:09,200 --> 00:39:11,400
l made a mistake
hiring you, Patterson.

532
00:39:11,400 --> 00:39:13,200
The world
is watching us.

533
00:39:13,200 --> 00:39:14,900
l need initiative,
not contraptions.

534
00:39:14,900 --> 00:39:16,600
l need
a professional hunter.

535
00:39:16,600 --> 00:39:18,700
l'm going to locate
Remington.

536
00:39:18,700 --> 00:39:20,600
l assume
you've heard of him.

537
00:39:20,600 --> 00:39:23,700
Every man who's ever hunted
has heard of him.

538
00:39:23,700 --> 00:39:25,800
l wish he were
here right now,

539
00:39:25,800 --> 00:39:27,300
but by the time
you find him,

540
00:39:27,300 --> 00:39:31,400
the lions will be dead,
and l'll be back on schedule.

541
00:39:33,900 --> 00:39:36,000
All right,
the job's still yours,

542
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:39,400
but only because it would take
too long to find a replacement.

543
00:39:39,400 --> 00:39:42,500
l'll go, but if l have to return,
you're finished.

544
00:39:42,500 --> 00:39:45,500
l will then do everything
within my considerable power

545
00:39:45,500 --> 00:39:47,100
to destroy
your reputation.

546
00:39:47,100 --> 00:39:48,600
Fair enough?

547
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:51,900
l told you
you'd hate me.

548
00:39:53,500 --> 00:39:57,100
Patterson's voice: Helena,
everything is collapsing on me.

549
00:39:57,100 --> 00:39:59,600
Every morning,
the ground is soaked with blood.

550
00:39:59,600 --> 00:40:03,900
The workers feel l brought this terror
since it didn't begin till my arrival.

551
00:40:03,900 --> 00:40:06,700
Whatever l try,
they seem to know.

552
00:40:06,700 --> 00:40:09,100
All the deaths are on me.

553
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:13,100
[Gunshots]

554
00:40:15,100 --> 00:40:16,800
Very good.
Very impressive.

555
00:40:16,800 --> 00:40:18,300
We've been hunting
since childhood.

556
00:40:18,300 --> 00:40:21,000
You're murderers,
criminals.

557
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:22,500
That's good.

558
00:40:22,500 --> 00:40:24,600
You'll be spending
your nights in there,

559
00:40:24,600 --> 00:40:27,600
and of course,
you'll have nothing to fear.

560
00:40:27,600 --> 00:40:29,400
That is correct.
Nothing.

561
00:40:50,800 --> 00:40:52,300
[Lion Growling]

562
00:40:52,300 --> 00:40:55,100
[Chimpanzees Screeching]

563
00:41:19,200 --> 00:41:20,200
[Gasp]

564
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:27,600
[Man Speaking
Foreign Language]

565
00:41:30,400 --> 00:41:32,000
[Roaring]

566
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:33,400
[Shouting
ln Foreign Language]

567
00:41:42,800 --> 00:41:44,800
Man: Fire! Fire!

568
00:41:44,800 --> 00:41:46,100
Fire!

569
00:41:58,800 --> 00:42:02,400
Fire! Fire!

570
00:42:02,400 --> 00:42:04,300
Fire!

571
00:42:08,500 --> 00:42:10,700
[Roaring]

572
00:42:14,900 --> 00:42:17,200
[Men Shouting
ln Foreign Language]

573
00:42:31,500 --> 00:42:34,300
[Roars]

574
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:52,700
Of course he kept moving!

575
00:42:52,700 --> 00:42:56,000
What did you want him to do,
sit down and pose for you?

576
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:59,900
Now, this worked.
He came in, hit the wire.

577
00:42:59,900 --> 00:43:03,300
He couldn't have been more than
15 feet away from the 3 of you,

578
00:43:03,300 --> 00:43:05,100
and you couldn't
even wound it!

579
00:43:05,100 --> 00:43:06,900
Should have given you
rocks, not rifles.

580
00:43:06,900 --> 00:43:08,800
There is not a trace
of blood anywhere.

581
00:43:08,800 --> 00:43:10,000
This is insane.

582
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:12,000
Man: l assure you,
we came close many times.

583
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:13,300
There must
be blood.

584
00:43:13,300 --> 00:43:14,900
The next time
will be better!

585
00:43:14,900 --> 00:43:19,000
Next time will be as this time!
The devil has come to Tsavo!

586
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:20,400
That's
ridiculous talk,

587
00:43:20,400 --> 00:43:21,900
and you don't
really believe it.

588
00:43:21,900 --> 00:43:23,800
Now you are
telling me my beliefs?

589
00:43:23,800 --> 00:43:25,200
l don't think so!

590
00:43:25,200 --> 00:43:27,900
l wasn't, and you know it,
so don't force it.

591
00:43:31,200 --> 00:43:34,300
Listen, we do
have a problem in Tsavo.

592
00:43:34,300 --> 00:43:37,400
Abdullah: At last, finally
we agree. You are right.

593
00:43:37,400 --> 00:43:39,100
We do!

594
00:43:39,100 --> 00:43:42,300
We do! You are
the problem in Tsavo!

595
00:43:42,300 --> 00:43:45,200
[Men Shouting]

596
00:43:45,200 --> 00:43:47,400
He is the problem
in Tsavo!

597
00:43:48,500 --> 00:43:50,000
You listen--

598
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:51,400
Be careful!

599
00:43:51,400 --> 00:43:53,600
You don't
tell me careful.

600
00:43:53,600 --> 00:43:55,600
You don't
tell me anything!

601
00:43:55,600 --> 00:43:57,800
[Men Shouting]

602
00:43:57,800 --> 00:44:01,100
Abdullah: We are sick
and tired of your lies!

603
00:44:01,100 --> 00:44:03,800
You listen
while l talk!

604
00:44:03,800 --> 00:44:04,900
[Cocks Gun]

605
00:44:04,900 --> 00:44:06,200
Change in plans.

606
00:44:06,200 --> 00:44:08,800
Get them back!
Now, get them all back!

607
00:44:08,800 --> 00:44:10,000
Get them back!

608
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:12,400
[Shouting
ln Foreign Language]

609
00:44:13,800 --> 00:44:16,100
Abdullah: Go back!
Quickly, go back!

610
00:44:16,100 --> 00:44:20,200
Go back!

611
00:44:21,500 --> 00:44:25,000
All right,
you listen while l talk

612
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:28,000
because you got a question
needs answering.

613
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:31,000
Will l pull this trigger?

614
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:33,500
You don't know all
that has happened here.

615
00:44:33,500 --> 00:44:35,000
He will pull
the trigger, Abdullah.

616
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:37,400
The devil has
come to Tsavo!

617
00:44:37,400 --> 00:44:38,400
Oh, you're right.

618
00:44:38,400 --> 00:44:42,700
The devil has come to Tsavo.
Look at me!

619
00:44:42,700 --> 00:44:46,600
l am the devil.

620
00:44:46,600 --> 00:44:49,500
l'm a man of peace!

621
00:44:51,200 --> 00:44:53,700
You sound like a man
who wants to live.

622
00:44:53,700 --> 00:44:57,400
Most certainly.
Absolutely. Yes.

623
00:44:57,400 --> 00:44:59,400
Well, that's
an excellent decision.

624
00:45:00,800 --> 00:45:02,100
Your name is Abdullah.

625
00:45:02,100 --> 00:45:03,800
Yes.

626
00:45:03,800 --> 00:45:06,100
Well, l'm sure we're
going to meet again.

627
00:45:06,100 --> 00:45:09,300
l think it's been
a pleasure.

628
00:45:10,800 --> 00:45:12,900
[Abdullah Shouting
ln Foreign Language]

629
00:45:15,300 --> 00:45:18,500
[Speaking
Foreign Language]

630
00:45:31,300 --> 00:45:34,800
[Shouting
ln Foreign Language]

631
00:45:34,800 --> 00:45:37,900
[Men Shouting
ln Foreign Language]

632
00:45:54,300 --> 00:45:56,800
[Chanting
ln Foreign Language]

633
00:46:11,100 --> 00:46:14,000
[Speaking
Foreign Language]

634
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:16,000
[Samuel Speaking
Foreign Language]

635
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:17,400
John Patterson.

636
00:46:17,400 --> 00:46:18,800
Aye.

637
00:46:23,300 --> 00:46:26,400
Samuel: Remington uses
the Masai to hunt lions.

638
00:46:26,400 --> 00:46:29,400
lt will cost you
10 head of cattle.

639
00:46:29,400 --> 00:46:31,900
He takes some
getting used to.

640
00:46:35,200 --> 00:46:38,100
Why didn't you tell me
you knew him?

641
00:46:38,100 --> 00:46:39,600
You did not ask.

642
00:46:44,800 --> 00:46:47,200
l didn't get a chance
to thank you.

643
00:46:47,200 --> 00:46:49,600
For what?
What did l do?

644
00:46:49,600 --> 00:46:51,000
Got me
out of trouble.

645
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:53,400
Oh, that was nothing.
Samuel was there.

646
00:46:53,400 --> 00:46:55,800
He would have
done something.

647
00:46:55,800 --> 00:46:58,200
What was that
all about, anyway?

648
00:46:58,200 --> 00:47:00,500
There are
over 40 dead.

649
00:47:00,500 --> 00:47:02,400
40? That's amazing.

650
00:47:02,400 --> 00:47:04,800
There's a few things
you should know about these lions.

651
00:47:04,800 --> 00:47:06,500
Let me save you time.

652
00:47:06,500 --> 00:47:09,500
Now, you're the engineer, and you're
in charge of building the bridge.

653
00:47:09,500 --> 00:47:10,900
Am l right so far?

654
00:47:10,900 --> 00:47:11,900
That's right.

655
00:47:11,900 --> 00:47:13,500
All right,
l am not an engineer,

656
00:47:13,500 --> 00:47:16,400
and l don't want to be in charge
of building that bridge.

657
00:47:16,400 --> 00:47:19,700
Now, l'm sure you probably
hate Tsavo as much as l do,

658
00:47:19,700 --> 00:47:24,200
and knowing Beaumont, you're not
the imbecile that he says you are,

659
00:47:24,200 --> 00:47:26,400
so what do you say
we help each other?

660
00:47:26,400 --> 00:47:28,200
Now, l'm going
to help you

661
00:47:28,200 --> 00:47:30,200
by killing the lions
and then leaving,

662
00:47:30,200 --> 00:47:32,000
and you're
going to help me

663
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:34,800
by doing what l say
so l can leave.

664
00:47:34,800 --> 00:47:36,600
You see a problem
with that?

665
00:47:36,600 --> 00:47:38,000
Actually, no.

666
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:41,000
Let us prepare
for battle.

667
00:47:46,600 --> 00:47:48,600
Whew!

668
00:47:48,600 --> 00:47:50,000
All right--
[Coughing]

669
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:52,400
Remington: First thing
l'm going to propose

670
00:47:52,400 --> 00:47:55,300
is a new hospital, and l want it
built by tomorrow night.

671
00:47:55,300 --> 00:47:57,600
What?
That's a terrible idea.

672
00:47:57,600 --> 00:48:00,000
Oh, l'm sorry. You must
be the doctor, right?

673
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:02,700
l'm sure you know
what's best.

674
00:48:02,700 --> 00:48:05,900
That's the most infantile thing
l've ever heard in my life.

675
00:48:05,900 --> 00:48:08,200
Now, whoever you are,
will you mind telling me

676
00:48:08,200 --> 00:48:11,000
why on earth we should
go through all that?

677
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:15,300
l suppose l could explain what, with
the scent of flesh and blood in here,

678
00:48:15,300 --> 00:48:17,200
it makes for
an inviting target.

679
00:48:17,200 --> 00:48:20,600
l suppose l could tell you
l just saw fresh paw prints out there

680
00:48:20,600 --> 00:48:24,100
which make me think they're already
thinking about feasting in here,

681
00:48:24,100 --> 00:48:27,000
but l don't want to answer you
because when you question me,

682
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:29,800
you are saying to me
that l don't know what l'm doing.

683
00:48:29,800 --> 00:48:34,200
Now, anybody here think l'm a fool,
then please speak up right now.

684
00:48:36,600 --> 00:48:37,800
Colonel Patterson...

685
00:48:42,800 --> 00:48:45,300
Well, then l guess
we all agree.

686
00:48:45,300 --> 00:48:47,600
[Men Chanting
ln Foreign Language]

687
00:49:09,400 --> 00:49:13,400
l'm going to need you
there with me tomorrow.

688
00:49:13,400 --> 00:49:15,000
Whatever you wish.

689
00:49:17,100 --> 00:49:18,400
Ahh.

690
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:22,000
Samuel says
you killed a lion.

691
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:24,300
lt was probably
just luck.

692
00:49:24,300 --> 00:49:28,100
Oh, nobody kills a lion
with one shot by luck.

693
00:49:28,100 --> 00:49:30,200
You might be useful
tomorrow.

694
00:49:30,200 --> 00:49:33,200
But even if you're not,
you should understand

695
00:49:33,200 --> 00:49:35,900
this may take me 2,
maybe 3 days to sort this out.

696
00:49:35,900 --> 00:49:37,200
But when l leave,

697
00:49:37,200 --> 00:49:39,900
you're still going to have
to build that bridge,

698
00:49:39,900 --> 00:49:42,400
so l don't want your men
to lose respect for you.

699
00:49:42,400 --> 00:49:43,800
That's very considerate
of you.

700
00:49:43,800 --> 00:49:45,800
Well, l'm
a very considerate man.

701
00:49:45,800 --> 00:49:47,600
My mother
taught me that.

702
00:49:47,600 --> 00:49:49,500
[Samuel Chuckles]

703
00:49:49,500 --> 00:49:51,100
Ha ha ha!

704
00:49:51,100 --> 00:49:53,300
Now, what the hell
you laughing about?

705
00:49:53,300 --> 00:49:55,200
You don't think
l'm considerate?

706
00:49:55,200 --> 00:49:56,600
l don't believe
you had a mother.

707
00:49:56,600 --> 00:49:58,000
[Spits]

708
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:00,000
Ha ha ha!

709
00:50:04,400 --> 00:50:06,600
[Speaking Foreign Language]

710
00:50:08,800 --> 00:50:11,700
[Men Singing
ln Foreign Language]

711
00:50:22,500 --> 00:50:26,000
Hawthorne: You really believe
you can make something happen?

712
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:27,000
Hmm?

713
00:50:28,300 --> 00:50:31,500
Hawthorne:
But you're not excited.

714
00:50:33,700 --> 00:50:36,100
Patterson: You don't
enjoy killing, do you?

715
00:50:39,100 --> 00:50:40,600
Then why do it?

716
00:50:42,800 --> 00:50:45,200
Because l've got a gift.

717
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:50,400
l'm going
to join them now.

718
00:50:50,400 --> 00:50:53,600
We have to try to convince
each other that we're still brave.

719
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:58,700
l wouldn't have thought bravery
would be a problem for you.

720
00:50:58,700 --> 00:51:00,300
Well, you hope each time
it won't be...

721
00:51:00,300 --> 00:51:02,600
but you never
really know.

722
00:51:08,100 --> 00:51:10,200
Strange man.

723
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:16,800
2 great tribes
of his country

724
00:51:16,800 --> 00:51:21,000
fought a terrible
civil war for many years.

725
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:22,400
And his side lost?

726
00:51:22,400 --> 00:51:23,700
Samuel:
Everything.

727
00:51:23,700 --> 00:51:25,400
Land and family.

728
00:51:25,400 --> 00:51:29,200
Very young ones
and the very old ones...

729
00:51:29,200 --> 00:51:31,700
all lost.

730
00:51:31,700 --> 00:51:35,600
He buried his family
and left his country forever.

731
00:51:35,600 --> 00:51:38,900
Now he hunts
all over the world,

732
00:51:38,900 --> 00:51:41,200
but he always
returns here.

733
00:51:41,200 --> 00:51:44,000
He says Africa
is the last good place.

734
00:51:45,500 --> 00:51:46,700
John?

735
00:51:48,800 --> 00:51:50,700
Will you exchange
weapons with me?

736
00:51:50,700 --> 00:51:52,300
Mine is
much more powerful.

737
00:51:52,300 --> 00:51:53,900
l won't be with you
tomorrow.

738
00:51:53,900 --> 00:51:55,500
l'll be finishing
the new hospital.

739
00:51:59,600 --> 00:52:00,900
Thank you.

740
00:52:06,100 --> 00:52:07,700
Why does he
need you with him?

741
00:52:07,700 --> 00:52:08,800
Samuel: He doesn't.

742
00:52:12,000 --> 00:52:14,400
We've hunted many times.

743
00:52:14,400 --> 00:52:17,600
He knows
l'm afraid of lions.

744
00:52:17,600 --> 00:52:20,000
[Men Chanting]

745
00:52:32,300 --> 00:52:34,400
[Cow Bellows]

746
00:53:31,300 --> 00:53:34,100
Well, l spotted at least
one of them in the thicket.

747
00:53:34,100 --> 00:53:36,100
Samuel,
you're coming with me.

748
00:53:42,400 --> 00:53:44,000
[Speaking
Foreign Language]

749
00:53:46,800 --> 00:53:47,800
[Speaking
Foreign Language]

750
00:54:24,100 --> 00:54:28,500
Chances are l'm going to
kill that lion in the thicket.

751
00:54:28,500 --> 00:54:31,700
Colonel, why don't you take
the higher position there
in case he gets through us?

752
00:54:31,700 --> 00:54:34,400
You'll have
a clear shot at him.

753
00:54:36,100 --> 00:54:38,800
[Whistles]

754
00:54:49,300 --> 00:54:51,800
[Whistles]

755
00:56:16,100 --> 00:56:17,700
Aah!

756
00:56:17,700 --> 00:56:20,700
[Men Hooting]

757
00:57:41,400 --> 00:57:44,300
[Roaring]

758
00:57:45,300 --> 00:57:46,500
[Click]

759
00:58:04,900 --> 00:58:06,400
Shoot him.

760
00:58:10,900 --> 00:58:12,300
Shoot him.

761
00:58:17,300 --> 00:58:20,000
Shoot him!
Goddamn it! Shoot him!

762
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:24,000
Shoot him!

763
00:58:34,900 --> 00:58:36,300
What happened?

764
00:58:36,300 --> 00:58:37,700
l don't know.

765
00:58:37,700 --> 00:58:40,400
What do you mean,
you don't know?

766
00:58:40,400 --> 00:58:41,800
Misfire.

767
00:58:41,800 --> 00:58:43,700
That the first time?

768
00:58:45,300 --> 00:58:48,500
The gun belongs
to Dr. Hawthorne.

769
00:58:54,500 --> 00:58:56,800
You exchanged weapons?

770
00:58:56,800 --> 00:59:01,800
You went into battle
with an unproven rifle?

771
00:59:04,500 --> 00:59:05,700
Whew!

772
00:59:08,800 --> 00:59:11,800
They got an expression
in prizefighting.

773
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:14,600
Everybody's got a plan
until they've been hit.

774
00:59:14,600 --> 00:59:15,900
Well, my friend...

775
00:59:15,900 --> 00:59:18,900
you've just been hit.

776
00:59:18,900 --> 00:59:20,200
The getting up...

777
00:59:20,200 --> 00:59:23,100
that's up to you.

778
00:59:23,100 --> 00:59:25,800
[Man Speaking
Foreign Language]

779
00:59:29,600 --> 00:59:32,900
[Man Continues Speaking
ln Foreign Language]

780
00:59:32,900 --> 00:59:35,800
Samuel: They say
